Collection numbers 131, 133=131, 134=131. The sheet has two (apparently unpublished) handwritten descriptions of a new species, the descriptions very similar: Nos 131 + 133 + 134. Cyperus pauciflorus n. sp. in ed. Plant 6-12 inches. Root tuberous - leaves clustered at base, shorter than the 3 angled culm. Umbels simple erect, 4-6 rayed with the central one sessile, shorter than the 3 leaved involucre; spikelets linear, 2 ranked, spreading + somewhat reflexted, 2-3 flowered, the uppermost abortive; scales obtuse, mucronate, compressed - keeled, nerved, reddish brown, points of the uppermost scales spreading or recurved at the apex; style 3 cleft â" nut oblong, 3 angled acute. Near C. repens + lutescens, but differing in the small number of florets + in the scales + nuts. Apr. 30/69. Near Corpus Christi Texas. HWR. Found Apr 30 1869, in damp flat near Corpus Christi Texas.
